<subSubSection id="C357652EFFD73926FF5FEF2BFA53FD9A" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FEF2BFA53FD9A" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FEF2BFE8EFE9B" bold="true" box="[199,321,294,319]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This genus can be separated from the other Australian 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FC34EF2BFB86FE9B" box="[940,1097,294,319]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Stratiomyidae</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: Eyes distinctly separated in both sexes and with sparse ommatrichia. Flagellomeres indistinct, at most represented by slight dorsal and/or ventral indentations; the first flagellomere is sometimes present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FAE5EF62FEC4FE0F" authority="Macquart, 1847" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Metoponia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FAE5EF62FEC4FE0F" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">M. robertsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE8AEF9FFEA3FE0F" bold="true" box="[274,364,402,427]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. sp.</emphasis>
Wings of male lacking discal medial cell, vein M 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FC38EFACFC67FE0B" box="[928,936,417,431]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="3.0">3</number>
absent; females apterous. Scutum of female without dorsal sutures and scutellum absent; scutum of male with usual sutures and scutellum present. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FE80EFD0FEB2FE52" box="[280,381,477,502]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FECAEFD0FEB2FE52" box="[338,381,477,502]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6–8</number>
</figureCitation>
) small; aedeagus single pronged. Gonocoxite medially attenuate distally, extending almost to apex of aedeagus. Epandrium (
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FD9CEC0CFD9DFDBE" box="[516,594,513,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FDFBEC0CFD4FFDBE" box="[611,640,513,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">26</figureCitation>
) with prominent posterior corners. Female terminalia (
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FA90EC0CFA40FDBE" box="[1288,1423,513,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[187,1351,193,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[187,1351,193,1905]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 15. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., female paratypes. (9). Head, lateral view. (10). Head, frontal view. (11). Lateral habitus. (12). Dorsal habitus. (13). Terminalia, dorsal view. (14). Terminalia, lateral view. (15). Terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: ce, cercus; st, sternite; tg, tergite. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266436/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FADEEC0CFA40FDBE" box="[1350,1423,513,538]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13–15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor not apparent; sternite 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FD90EC2BFDD9FD9A" box="[520,534,550,574]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
viewed ventrally, is convex and longer than combined length of tergites 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FADBEC2BFA9EFD9A" box="[1347,1361,550,574]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
and 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FA1FEC2BFA57FD9A" box="[1415,1432,550,574]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="9.0">9</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C357652EFFD73926FF5FEC44FD60FB6C" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FEC44FB05FD55" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FEC44FE52FDC6" bold="true" box="[199,413,585,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Description. Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FE33EC44FDDEFDC6" box="[427,529,585,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FE7DEC47FE3FFDC6" box="[485,496,586,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="1.0">1</number>
–8
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FD85EC44FDA7FDC6" box="[541,616,585,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
22– 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FDD3EC44FDA7FDC6" box="[587,616,585,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FDE3EC44FD75FDC6" bold="true" box="[635,698,585,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FD52EC44FCE0FDC6" box="[714,815,585,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FC9BEC47FCC2FDC6" box="[771,781,586,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="1.0">1</number>
–2
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FCA4EC47FC94FDC6" box="[828,859,586,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">23</figureCitation>
). Yellow-brown with short erect setae; transversely broadened; ocellar tubercle black or black brown and raised above vertex. Frons visible when viewed laterally especially in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FEB7EC9FFE05FD0D" authority="Macquart, 1847" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" box="[303,458,657,681]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Metoponia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FEB7EC9FFE05FD0D" box="[303,458,657,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">M. robertsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE4BEC9CFDE8FD0E" bold="true" box="[467,551,657,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. sp</emphasis>
. Frontal index 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FD42EC9CFCFEFD0E" box="[730,817,657,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="0.65" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.8</number>
. Ratio of frons width to head width 1.0:2.0– 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FAABEC9CFA96FD0E" box="[1331,1369,657,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="2.6">2.6</number>
. Eyes distinctly separated and with sparse ommatrichia. Flagellomeres indistinct, at most represented by slight dorsal and/or ventral indentations; the first flagellomere is sometimes present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FC49ECD7FBA5FD55" authority="Macquart, 1847" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" box="[977,1130,729,753]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Metoponia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FC49ECD7FBA5FD55" box="[977,1130,729,753]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">M. robertsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FBE8ECD4FB0DFD56" bold="true" box="[1136,1218,729,754]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. sp</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FECF0FD3CFC21" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FECF0FEEFFCB2" bold="true" box="[199,288,765,790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Thorax</emphasis>
about 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FEEFECF0FE55FCB2" box="[375,410,765,790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times longer than wide and entirely yellowish brown or deep brown, with scutellum, humeral callus, postalar callus and laterotergite yellowish. Anepisternum shining, mostly devoid of setae. Wings (
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FF07ED48FF29FCFA" box="[159,230,837,862]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FF40ED4BFF29FCFA" box="[216,230,838,862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FE87ED4BFEF3FCFA" box="[287,316,838,862]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FE87ED4BFEF3FCFA" box="[287,316,838,862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
) about 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FE0AED48FE7BFCFA" box="[402,436,837,862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="2.5">2.5</number>
–3.0 times longer than wide and lacking discal medial cell and vein M 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FB4BED59FB14FCC6" box="[1235,1243,852,866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="3.0">3</number>
. Legs yellowish. First tarsomere on all legs shorter or longer than tibia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FED9DFCB8FC55" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FED9DFEF3FC0D" bold="true" box="[199,316,912,937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Abdomen</emphasis>
yellowish uniformly covered with short suberect setae. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FBE4ED9DFB2DFC0D" box="[1148,1250,912,937]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FB2EED9DFB0AFC0D" box="[1206,1221,912,937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="6.0">6</number>
–8
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FB77ED9DFAF8FC0D" box="[1263,1335,912,937]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
25– 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FA82ED9DFAF8FC0D" box="[1306,1335,912,937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
) broadly triangular to subquadrate. Cerci one segmented. Gonostyli concave distally. Aedeagus single pronged. Gonocoxite medially attenuate distally, extending almost to apex of aedeagus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FEDF1FAE2FB9D" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FEDF1FED1FBB1" bold="true" box="[199,286,1020,1045]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FEB7EDF1FE69FBB1" box="[303,422,1020,1045]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[187,1351,193,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[187,1351,193,1905]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 15. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., female paratypes. (9). Head, lateral view. (10). Head, frontal view. (11). Lateral habitus. (12). Dorsal habitus. (13). Terminalia, dorsal view. (14). Terminalia, lateral view. (15). Terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: ce, cercus; st, sternite; tg, tergite. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266436/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FEF3EDF1FE69FBB1" box="[363,422,1020,1045]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="12.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="9.0">9–15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Differing from male by being apterous and lacking halters, scutellum and most lateral thoracic pleura. Head (figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FE50EA2DFDCAFB9C" box="[456,517,1056,1080]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="9.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="9.0">9–10</number>
). Frontal index 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FD2DEA2DFCC2FB9D" box="[693,781,1056,1081]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="0.6499999999999999" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.7</number>
. Ratio of frons width to head width 1.0: 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FB4AEA2DFAE5FB9D" box="[1234,1322,1056,1081]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="2.55" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="2.5">2.5–2.6</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FEA49FD8DFB25" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FEA49FEE9FBF9" bold="true" box="[199,294,1092,1117]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Thorax.</emphasis>
Scutum without dorsal sutures and scutellum. Wings absent, halters absent. Legs shorter than male and first tarsomere shorter than tibiae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FEA81FD60FB6C" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FEA81FE8CFB01" bold="true" box="[199,323,1164,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Terminalia (
<figureCitation id="13762A20FFD73926FE41EA81FD90FB01" box="[473,607,1164,1189]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[187,1351,193,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[187,1351,193,1905]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 15. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., female paratypes. (9). Head, lateral view. (10). Head, frontal view. (11). Lateral habitus. (12). Dorsal habitus. (13). Terminalia, dorsal view. (14). Terminalia, lateral view. (15). Terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: ce, cercus; st, sternite; tg, tergite. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266436/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FD8DEA81FD90FB01" box="[533,607,1164,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13–15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor is not apparent; sternite 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FB8EEA80FBEBFB01" box="[1046,1060,1165,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
viewed ventrally is convex and longer than combined length of tergites 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FDCEEABDFDABFB6C" box="[598,612,1200,1224]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
and 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FD03EABDFD63FB6C" box="[667,684,1200,1224]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="9.0">9</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C357652EFFD73926FF5FEAD9FBCAFA91" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FEAD9FB0FFAB5" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FEAD9FE81FB49" bold="true" box="[199,334,1236,1261]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the genus comes from the Greek 
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FC09EAD9FC34FB48" box="[913,1019,1236,1260]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">metridios</emphasis>
, filled with seed, pertaining to the enlarged ovaries of the 
<typeStatus id="54F68807FFD73926FE05EAF4FE02FAB5" box="[413,461,1273,1297]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">type</typeStatus>
species which occupy most of the abdominal and thoracic cavities.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FEB11FBCAFA91" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" box="[199,1029,1308,1333]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FEB11FE3CFA91" bold="true" box="[199,499,1308,1333]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Geographic Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F35A7635FFD73926FE62EB11FDAEFA91" box="[506,609,1308,1333]" name="Australia" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Australia</collectingCountry>
(Queensland and New South 
<collectingCountry id="F35A7635FFD73926FC28EB11FC36FA91" box="[944,1017,1308,1333]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Wales</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C357652EFFD73926FF5FEB4DFB10F964" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF236A5FFD73926FF5FEB4DFB10F964" blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF5FEB4DFE80FAFD" bold="true" box="[199,335,1344,1369]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Comments.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FEC1EB4DFE09FAFC" box="[345,454,1344,1368]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE48EB4DFDF2FAFD" bold="true" box="[464,573,1344,1369]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FD42EB4CFCE9FAFC" box="[730,806,1345,1368]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FD42EB4CFCE9FAFC" box="[730,806,1345,1368]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having eyes with sparse ommatrichia; in males the flagellum is at least three times as long as the combined length of the scape and pedicel, and the eyes are distinctly separated; females are apterous and lack scutal sutures and scutellum. From 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FC65EB85FBA2FA04" box="[1021,1133,1416,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FC65EB85FBA2FA04" box="[1021,1133,1416,1440]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FB49EB85FA84FA04" box="[1233,1355,1416,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FB49EB85FA84FA04" box="[1233,1355,1416,1440]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, 
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF0FEBA1FECBFA60" box="[151,260,1452,1476]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE94EBA1FEB9FA61" bold="true" box="[268,374,1452,1477]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
differs in having an almost flat frons. Female 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FC10EBA1FC36FA60" box="[904,1017,1452,1476]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FC10EBA1FC36FA60" box="[904,1017,1452,1476]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are micropterous, having vestiges of the wings and halters, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FE23EBDCFD98FA4C" authority="Macquart, 1847" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" box="[443,599,1488,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Metoponia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE23EBDCFE1DFA4C" box="[443,466,1489,1512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE7BEBDDFD98FA4C" box="[483,599,1488,1512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">robertsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FDF8EBDDFD74FA4D" bold="true" box="[608,699,1488,1513]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. sp.</emphasis>
they are entirely absent. The ovipositor of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FB2AEBDDFAEDFA4C" box="[1202,1314,1488,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FB2AEBDDFAEDFA4C" box="[1202,1314,1488,1512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and many 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FF0FEBF9FEDEF9A8" box="[151,273,1524,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF0FEBF9FEDEF9A8" box="[151,273,1524,1548]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is comprised of segments 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FDD2EBF9FDB8F9A9" box="[586,631,1524,1549]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="6.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="5.0">5–8</number>
; in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FD3EEBF8FD3DF9A8" box="[678,754,1525,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FD3EEBF8FD3DF9A8" box="[678,754,1525,1548]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the ovipositor is comprised of segments 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FB4CEBF8FB2DF9A8" box="[1236,1250,1525,1548]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="7.0">7</number>
and 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FA87EBF8FAE1F9A9" box="[1311,1326,1525,1549]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
, while in 
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF0FE815FECBF994" box="[151,260,1560,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE93E815FEBCF995" bold="true" box="[267,371,1560,1585]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
the ovipositor is not well developed. Sternite 
<quantity id="4CB59B40FFD73926FCEFE815FC6DF995" box="[887,930,1560,1585]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" unit="in" value="8.0">8 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FC30E815FBEDF994" box="[936,1058,1560,1584]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FC30E815FBEDF994" box="[936,1058,1560,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FBA8E814FBB3F994" box="[1072,1148,1561,1584]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FBA8E814FBB3F994" box="[1072,1148,1561,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FB2BE815FAEBF994" box="[1203,1316,1560,1584]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FB2BE815FAEBF994" box="[1203,1316,1560,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more or less flat and tapers distally, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FE68E830FDF3F9F0" box="[496,572,1597,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE68E830FDF3F9F0" box="[496,572,1597,1620]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is almost square, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FCD9E831FC7DF9F0" box="[833,946,1596,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FCD9E831FC7DF9F0" box="[833,946,1596,1620]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FC73E831FBAAF9F0" box="[1003,1125,1596,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FC73E831FBAAF9F0" box="[1003,1125,1596,1620]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is about twice as long as wide; in 
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF60E86DFEAAF9DC" box="[248,357,1632,1656]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FEF4E86DFE1AF9DD" bold="true" box="[364,469,1632,1657]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
sternite 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FDACE86DFD8DF9DC" box="[564,578,1632,1656]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
is convex, its length subequal to its basal width, and the apical margin about half the basal width. Tergite 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FE77E888FE32F939" box="[495,509,1669,1693]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
and sternite 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FD04E888FD65F939" box="[668,682,1669,1693]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
are subequal in length in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FC71E889FB96F938" box="[1001,1113,1668,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FC71E889FB96F938" box="[1001,1113,1668,1692]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FBF4E888FB77F938" box="[1132,1208,1669,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FBF4E888FB77F938" box="[1132,1208,1669,1692]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D26FFD73926FB60E889FABDF938" box="[1272,1394,1668,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FB60E889FABDF938" box="[1272,1394,1668,1692]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; in 
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FF0FE8A5FECBF964" box="[151,260,1704,1728]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B939EAB7FFD73926FE93E8A5FEBCF965" bold="true" box="[267,371,1704,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
, the combined length of tergites 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FD7DE8A5FD3CF964" box="[741,755,1704,1728]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
and 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FCB1E8A5FCF8F964" box="[809,823,1704,1728]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="9.0">9</number>
approximates the length of sternite 
<number id="3D852482FFD73926FB52E8A5FB15F964" box="[1226,1242,1704,1728]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
.
</paragraph>
